PUH-BrianMartell This A&A Letters paper (aa56581-25, published Dec 2025) reports JWST NIRSpec and NIRCam observations of GRB 250314A at z ≈ 7.3 — one of the highest-redshift GRBs known. The key discovery: a bright, broad emission feature in the NIR that is best explained as a pair-instability supernova (PISN) or similar extremely energetic supernova exploding alongside the GRB. Main findings: •  The GRB afterglow fades normally, but a persistent, very red source remains. •  Spectroscopy shows a broad emission complex centered around rest-frame ~5000 Å, consistent with a massive SN (likely >100 M⊙ progenitor) rich in heavy elements. •  Photometry rules out normal Type Ic SN; requires extreme energy release characteristic of pair-instability or similar. •  Host galaxy is compact, low-mass, but metal-enriched — unusual for z~7.3.
